Colonel '''William Merriman''' [[Order of the Indian Empire|CIE]] (2 April 1838 – 11 March 1917) was a British officer in the [[Royal Engineers]] who played as a [[goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] in three [[FA Cup Final]]s, winning the cup in [[1875 FA Cup Final|1875]].

==Family and education==
Merriman was born at 13 Young Street, [[Kensington]], London on 2 April 1838{{Sfn|Warsop|2004|page=106}}{{ref|A|a}}, the eighth of nine children of Dr John Merriman (1800–1881) and his wife Caroline née Jones (1800–1870), and was baptised at [[St Mary Abbots|St Mary Abbots Church]], Kensington on 25 May 1838.<ref>{{cite web|title=William Merriman in the London, England, Births and Baptisms, 1813–1906|url=http://search.ancestry.co.uk/cgi-bin/sse.dll?db=LMAbirths&h=8718378&ti=5538&indiv=try&gss=pt&ssrc=pt_t76112142_p34345737555_kpidz0q3d34345737555z0q26pgz0q3d32768z0q26pgplz0q3dpid|website=ancestry.co.uk|accessdate=19 January 2015|subscription=yes}}</ref> His father, grandfather John (1774–1839) and uncle James Nathaniel (1806–1854) were all physicians to HM Queen Victoria.<ref name =DNB>{{cite DNB|first1=Gordon|last1= Goodwin |wstitle=Merriman, Samuel (1771–1852)|volume=37}}</ref>

Merriman was educated at [[Kensington School]],{{Sfn|Warsop|2004|page=106}} before attending [[Addiscombe Military Seminary]] (where officers were trained for service with the army of the [[East India Company]]) in 1856.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Vibart |first1=Col Henry Meredith |title=Addiscombe: Its Heroes and  Men of Note |date=1894 |url=https://ia600400.us.archive.org/9/items/addiscombeitsher00viba/addiscombeitsher00viba.pdf |accessdate=19 January 2015|page=657}}</ref>

==Military career==
He joined the East India Company's Royal Engineers with the rank of [[Ensign (rank)|ensign]] on 12 December 1856{{Sfn|Warsop|2004|page=106}} "during the period of his being placed under the command of Colonel Sandham, of the Royal Engineers, at Chatham, for Field Instructions in the art of Sapping and Mining",<ref>{{LondonGazette |issue=21987|startpage=1300|date= 10 April 1857 |accessdate= 19 January 2015}}</ref> and was promoted to Lieutenant on 13 August 1858.<ref>{{LondonGazette |issue=22173|startpage=3789|date= 13 August 1858 |accessdate= 19 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{LondonGazette |issue=22621|startpage=2241|date= 29 April 1862|accessdate= 19 January 2015}}</ref> He served as an [[adjutant]] at [[Pune|Poona]] in India from 1858 to 1866, before returning to [[Chatham Dockyard|Chatham]] as a fieldwork instructor.{{Sfn|Warsop|2004|page=106}} Merriman was promoted to [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|Captain]] on 31 December 1868<ref>{{LondonGazette |issue=23465|startpage=598|date= 5 February 1869 |accessdate= 19 January 2015}}</ref> and to [[Major (United Kingdom)|Major]] on 13 March 1874.<ref>{{LondonGazette |issue=24082|startpage=1923|date= 31 March 1874 |accessdate= 19 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{LondonGazette |issue=24094|startpage=2507|date= 12 May 1874 |accessdate= 19 January 2015}}</ref> Between 1875 and 1881, he was District Officer at [[Colchester Garrison|Colchester]].{{Sfn|Warsop|2004|page=106}}

He was promoted to [[Lieutenant colonel (United Kingdom)|Lieutenant Colonel]] on 1 July 1881,<ref>{{LondonGazette |issue=25089|startpage=1414|date= 28 March 1882 |accessdate= 19 January 2015}}</ref> and then saw active service in South Africa, before spending the remainder of his military career in India, where he was involved with the coastal defences in West India from 1882.{{Sfn|Warsop|2004|page=106}} On 1 July 1885, he was promoted to [[Colonel (United Kingdom)|Colonel]],<ref>{{LondonGazette |issue=25489|startpage=3183|date= 10 July 1885|accessdate= 19 January 2015}}</ref> becoming chief engineer on the staff of Sir [[George Greaves (British Army officer)|George Greaves]], the [[Bombay Army#Commanders in Chief|Commander in Chief]] at Bombay, in 1892, before retiring the following year.{{Sfn|Warsop|2004|page=106}}

On 1 January 1890, Merriman was created a Companion of the [[Order of the Indian Empire]] (CIE) in the [[1890 New Year Honours|New Year Honours list]],<ref>{{LondonGazette |issue=26008|startpage=1|date= 1 January 1890 |accessdate= 19 January 2015}}</ref>{{Sfn|Harrison|1905|page=146}} for "services involving the coast defences in India and Aden".{{Sfn|Warsop|2004|page=106}}

==Sporting career==
Merriman was a keen all-round sportsman and participated in athletics, rowing, golf, hunting and shooting as well as cricket and football.{{Sfn|Warsop|2004|page=106}} He represented the Royal Engineers at cricket, playing regularly between 1869 and 1879.<ref>{{cite web|title=Miscellaneous Matches Played by William Merriman |url=http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/332/332436/Miscellaneous_Matches.html|publisher=Cricket Archive|accessdate=20 January 2015}}</ref>

In India, Merriman was vice-commodore of the [[Royal Bombay Yacht Club]] and a steward at the [[Bombay Turf Club]].{{Sfn|Warsop|2004|page=106}}

===Football career===
[[File:RoyalEngineers1872.jpg|thumb|300px|right|The Royal Engineers team of 1872. Eight of these players played in the first FA Cup Final. Merriman is standing first on the left]]
Merriman represented the Addiscombe Military Seminary at [[association football|football]] in 1856, before his service in India. During his period of service in England between 1867 and 1881, he was a regular member of the [[Royal Engineers A.F.C.|Royal Engineers]] football team, generally playing in [[goalkeeper (association football)|goal]]. Contemporaries described him as "the most popular of football chiefs", "as a goalkeeper (he) is never found wanting", "one of the very best goalkeepers of the day, plucky, cool and difficult to pass" and "always doing the right thing at the right time".{{Sfn|Warsop|2004|page=106}} The ''Royal Engineers Journal'' described Merriman as "an uncommonly good goal-keeper, a fact not infrequently mentioned in the records of matches".{{Sfn|Warsop|2004|page=11}}

In November 1871, the Royal Engineers were among fifteen teams who entered [[1871–72 FA Cup|the inaugural FA Cup competition]], and were allocated a home match in the first round against [[Reigate Priory F.C.|Reigate Priory]]. Reigate Priory, however, withdrew from the competition, sending the Engineers through to the next round on a [[walkover]]. In the second round, the Engineers beat [[Hitchin F.C.|Hitchin]] 5–0 on 10 January 1872.<ref name="RS">{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/engcup1872.html|title=England FA Challenge Cup 1871–72|publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|date=27 January 2001|accessdate=20 January 2015}}</ref>{{Sfn|Collett|2003|pages=527–528}} At the quarter-final stage, the Engineers beat [[Hampstead Heathens F.C.|Hampstead Heathens]] 3–0, setting up a semi-final against [[Crystal Palace F.C. (1861)|Crystal Palace]] which was won 3–0 after a replay.<ref name="RS" />{{Sfn|Collett|2003|pages=527–528}}

[[1872 FA Cup Final|The first FA Cup Final]] was played at [[Kennington Oval]] on 16 March 1872 between the Royal Engineers and [[Wanderers F.C.|Wanderers]], the top amateur club of the day. Wanderers took the lead fifteen minutes into the game when [[Morton Betts]] opened the scoring from an acute angle after [[Robert Vidal]]'s long dribble. After twenty minutes Alcock put the ball past Merriman in the Engineers' goal, but the goal was disallowed because [[Charles Wollaston]] had handled the ball.{{Sfn|Warsop|2004|page=40}} Wanderers continued to exert further pressure on the Engineers' goal and only Merriman's skill was able to prevent them from increasing their lead. Despite a late rally from the Engineers, Wanderers were able to hold on to their lead and the game ended in a 1–0 victory in their favour.{{Sfn|Gibbons|2001|pages=35–36}}<ref>{{cite web|title=1872 FA Cup Final: Wanderers vs Royal Engineers|url=http://www.fa-cupfinals.co.uk/1872.html |website=www.fa-cupfinals.co.uk|accessdate=20 January 2015}}</ref>

Merriman's performance in goal was described by ''The Field'' as "perfect".{{Sfn|Warsop|2004|page=11, 106}} ''The Sportsman'' reported that "more than one (attack) would doubtless have been successful but for the extremely efficient goal-keeping of Capt Merriman".{{Sfn|Warsop|2004|page=11}} ''The Field'' further commented that "so resolute was the front offered by Capt Merriman, the goal keeper of the Sappers, and so judicious his defence, that further reverses were averted for his side" and "to him alone was due the preservation of the military fortress from further surrenders".{{Sfn|Warsop|2004|page=11}}

In [[1872–73 FA Cup|the following year]], the Royal Engineers were eliminated from the FA Cup in the third round following a 1–0 defeat by [[Oxford University A.F.C.|Oxford University]],{{Sfn|Collett|2003|pages=527–528}} but in [[1873–74 FA Cup|1874]] they easily reached the final, with victories in the early rounds of 5–0 and 7–0 over [[Brondesbury F.C.|Brondesbury]] and [[Maidenhead United F.C.|Maidenhead]] respectively.{{Sfn|Collett|2003|pages=527–528}} In [[1874 FA Cup Final|the final]], played at Kennington Oval on 14 March 1874, the Engineers faced Oxford University. The university won the match 2–0 with early goals from [[Charles Mackarness]] and [[Frederick Patton]].<ref>{{cite web|title=FA Cup Final: 1874: Oxford University 2 Royal Engineers 0 |url=http://www.fa-cupfinals.co.uk/1874.html |website=www.fa-cupfinals.co.uk|accessdate=20 January 2015}}</ref> For the first goal, Merriman was unsighted when the ball was put past him from a melee after a corner.{{Sfn|Warsop|2004|page=31}} A match report by the Royal Engineers' secretary commented: "it was rather disgusting losing a goal like this for anyone almost could have stopped, but naturally enough each thought it safer to leave it to the goal-keeper who could use his hands to it; unfortunately, however, owing to the crowd he did not see it and thus the ball went quietly through the posts".{{Sfn|Warsop|2004|page=31}} For the second goal, the Royal Engineers' secretary reported that "[[Cuthbert Ottaway|Ottaway]] and [[Frederick Maddison (footballer)|Maddison]] failed to elude the Sappers' goal keeper who this time determined to die hard; his efforts were to no purpose for Patton coming to the rescue, shot the ball through the posts".{{Sfn|Warsop|2004|page=31}}

The Engineers reached the FA Cup Final for the third time in four years in [[1874–75 FA Cup|1875]] but only after a hard semi-final against Oxford University, with a 1–1 draw followed by a 1–0 victory in the replay, achieved by a goal in extra time from Capt [[Henry Renny-Tailyour]].{{Sfn|Collett|2003|pages=527–528}} In [[1875 FA Cup Final|the final]], played on 13 March 1875 at The Oval, the Engineers met the [[Old Etonians F.C.|Old Etonians]]. The match was played in a strong gale and the Engineers spent most of the match against the gale, with the rules requiring ends to be changed after each goal.<ref>{{cite web|title=FA Cup Final: 1875: Royal Engineers 2 Old Etonians 0 (First leg: 1–1)|url=http://www.fa-cupfinals.co.uk/1875.html |website=www.fa-cupfinals.co.uk|accessdate=20 January 2015}}</ref> [[Alexander Bonsor]] scored for the Old Boys after 30 minutes; ''The Sportsman'' reported that "the ball was so skilfully handled by Bonsor, with the proper allowance for the wind, that it went between the posts before Major Merriman could divert its course".{{Sfn|Warsop|2004|page=32}} Capt Renny-Tailyour scored an equaliser within five minutes and, later in the match, Merriman just managed to prevent [[Arthur Kinnaird, 11th Lord Kinnaird|Arthur Kinnaird]] scoring the winning goal and, despite extra time being played, the match ended 1–1.{{Sfn|Warsop|2004|page=43}} The replay was three days later; although the Engineers were able to field the same eleven as in the first match, the Etonians had to make four changes, losing the match 2–0, with both the Engineers' goals scored by Capt Renny-Tailyour.{{Sfn|Warsop|2004|page=44}} At the third attempt, Merriman (aged 36 years 348 days) and the Royal Engineers won their first, and only, FA Cup Final.{{Sfn|Gibbons|2001|pages=44–45}}

In [[1875–76 FA Cup|1875–76]], the Engineers defeated [[High Wycombe F.C.|High Wycombe]] 15–0 in the first round of the cup, before going out 3–1 to [[Swifts F.C.|Swifts]],{{Sfn|Collett|2003|pages=527–528}} and in [[1876–77 FA Cup|the following year]] they were eliminated in a fourth round defeat by [[Cambridge University A.F.C.|Cambridge University]].{{Sfn|Collett|2003|pages=527–528}}

Merriman served on the [[Football Association|FA]] committee between 1874 and 1877.{{Sfn|Warsop|2004|page=106}}

===Tributes===
In the September 1896 edition of ''The Sapper'', a memoir was published praising Merriman's contribution to sport at the Royal Engineers:{{Sfn|Warsop|2004|page=106}}

{{quote|text=Who does not remember the Major Merriman of twenty years ago who was never more delighted than when organizing sports – football, cricket and other matches – for the sapper's pleasure? I can see him now, in winter time, coming out on the Barrack Square with a football under his arm and giving a mighty kick, shouting out for the men to come and join him, and in less time than I can write it, the barracks would be swarming and there would be rare fun.}}

==Personal life==
Merriman married Emily Jane Anna Elizabeth Somerset (1851–1923) at [[St Stephen's, Gloucester Road|St Stephen's Church]], South Kensington on 13 February 1872.<ref>{{cite web|title=William Merriman in the London, England, Marriages and Banns, 1754–1921|url=http://search.ancestry.co.uk/cgi-bin/sse.dll?db=LMAmarriages&h=4382568&ti=5538&indiv=try&gss=pt&ssrc=pt_t76112142_p34345737555_kpidz0q3d34345737555z0q26pgz0q3d32768z0q26pgplz0q3dpid|website=ancestry.co.uk|accessdate=21 January 2015|subscription=yes}}</ref> She was the great-granddaughter of [[Henry Somerset, 5th Duke of Beaufort]] and the daughter of Colonel FitzRoy Molyneux Henry Somerset, also an officer in the [[Royal Engineers]], and Jemima Drummond Nairne.<ref>{{cite web|title=Emily Jane Anna Elizabeth Somerset|url=http://thepeerage.com/p26765.htm#i267646|website=thepeerage.com|accessdate=21 January 2015|date=16 February 2008}}</ref> Her brother, [[Arthur Somerset senior|Arthur]], played first-class cricket for [[Sussex County Cricket Club|Sussex]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Arthur Somerset|url=http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/32/32932/32932.html|publisher=Cricket Archive|accessdate=21 January 2015}}</ref> The couple had four children:<ref>{{cite web|title=Emily J. A. E. Merriman in the 1881 England Census |url=http://search.ancestry.co.uk/cgi-bin/sse.dll?db=uki1881&h=5138166&ti=5538&indiv=try&gss=pt&ssrc=pt_t76112142_p34345738127_kpidz0q3d34345738127z0q26pgz0q3d32768z0q26pgplz0q3dpid |website=ancestry.co.uk|accessdate=21 January 2015|subscription=yes}}</ref> 
*Ethel Fitzroy Merriman (1873–1960)
*Arthur Drummond Nairne Merriman (1876–1966)
*Blanche Merriman (1878–1968)
*Dorothy Gladys Merriman (1880–1968)

William Merriman died at the family home at Creffield House, Gray Road, [[Colchester]], Essex on 11 March 1917, aged 78.<ref>{{cite web |title=England & Wales, National Probate Calendar (Index of Wills and Administrations), 1858–1966 for William Merriman |url=http://interactive.ancestry.co.uk/1904/31874_223137-00247/6026594?backurl=http%3a%2f%2fsearch.ancestry.co.uk%2f%2fcgi-bin%2fsse.dll%3fdb%3dUKProbateCal%26h%3d6026594%26ti%3d5538%26indiv%3dtry%26gss%3dpt%26ssrc%3dpt_t76112142_p34345737555_kpidz0q3d34345737555z0q26pgz0q3d32768z0q26pgplz0q3dpid&ssrc=pt_t76112142_p34345737555_kpidz0q3d34345737555z0q26pgz0q3d32768z0q26pgplz0q3dpid&backlabel=ReturnRecord |website=ancestry.co.uk|accessdate=21 January 2015|subscription=yes}}</ref>

==Note==
*{{note|A|a}} The family home at 13 Young Street, Kensington was later the home of the novelist, [[William Makepeace Thackeray]] and the poet, [[George Bernard O'Neill|G. B. O'Neill]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Young Street, London|url=http://www.library.upenn.edu/collections/rbm/photos/biswanger/thackeray-1846.html |website= www.library.upenn.edu|publisher=Raymond Biswanger Slide Collection|accessdate=21 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Kensington Square and environs: Young Street, Thackeray Street and South End|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/survey-london/vol42/pp46-54|publisher=British History Online |accessdate=21 January 2015}}</ref> 

